<theorem xml:id="th_isom_structure">
<title>Isomorphisms preserve structure</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>T\colon V\rightarrow W</m> be an isomorphism. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            A tuple <m>S=(v_i)_{i\in I}</m> of vectors in <m>V</m> is linearly independent if and only if its image  <m>T(S)=(T(v_i))_{i\in I}</m> is linearly independent.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>W=\Span S</m>, where <m>S=(v_i)_{i\in I}</m> is a tuple in <m>V</m>. We have
            <men xml:id="eq_isom_image">
                T(W)=T(\Span S)=\Span T(S)=\Span (T(v_i))_{i\in I}
            </men>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>B=(v_i)_{i\in I}</m> is a basis of <m>V</m> if and only if <m>T(B)=(T(v_i))_{i\in I}</m> is a basis of <m>W</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>V</m> is finite-dimensional if and only if <m>W</m> is finite-dimensional, and in this case we have <m>\dim V=\dim W</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>U</m> is a subspace of <m>V</m> if and only if <m>T(U)</m> is a subspace of <m>W</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have <m>V=V_1\oplus V_2</m> for subspaces <m>V_i\subseteq V</m> if and only if <m>W=T(V_1)\oplus T(V_2)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<corollary xml:id="cor_isom_finite_dim">
    <title>Finite-dimensional spaces</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be finite dimensional vector spaces. The following statements are equivalent. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>V</m> is isomorphic to <m>W</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\dim V=\dim W</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>
<definition xml:id="d_coor_vect">
<title>Coordinate vectors</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>B=(v_i)_{i\in I}</m> be a basis of the vector space <m>V</m>. Given <m>v\in V</m>, let <m>v=\sum_{i\in I}c_iv_i</m> be the unique expression of <m>v</m> as a linear combination of the <m>v_i</m>. We define the tuple of scalars <m>(c_i)_{i\in I}\in F^I</m> to be the <term>coordinate vector</term> of <m>v</m> with respect to <m>B</m>, denoted <m>[v]_B</m>: <ie/>, 
<men xml:id="eq_coor_vec">
    [v]_B=(c_i)_{i\in I}
</men>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_coor_vec">
<title>Coordinate vector map</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>B=(v_i)_{i\in I}</m> be a basis of the vector space <m>V</m> and define 
<md>
    <mrow>T\colon V\amp \rightarrow F^I</mrow>
    <mrow>v \amp \longmapsto [v]_B</mrow>
</md>.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Show that <m>T</m> is an injective linear transformation. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Prove that if <m>\dim V&lt; \infty</m>, then <m>T</m> is an isomorphism. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Given an example where <m>T</m> is not an isomorphism. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
